\section*{Chapter 10}

\section*{$dk$-series}

\textbf{Note:} all models covered in this chapter are \textit{microcanonical}.

\section*{10.1 Motivation}

\begin{itemize}
\item ER vs. CM:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{c|c|c}
& ``reproduces'' $\approx$ & \\
ER & ``models well'' $\approx$ & the average degree $k$ \\
& ``is a good model of'' $=$ & \\
& is the correct null model of & \\
\hline
CM & $\dots$ // $\dots$ & the degree distribution $P(k)$
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\item The degree distribution ``defines, fixes'' the average degree; it provides more detailed information about the network structure:
\[
\bar{k} = \sum_k k P(k) \iff 2m = \sum_{i=1}^n k_i.
\]

\item The CM$(n, \mathbf{k})$ graphs form a subset of $\mathcal{G}(n, m)$ graph with $m = \frac{1}{2} \sum k_i$:

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\textit{[A hand-drawn diagram showing nested regions. The outermost region is labeled $\mathcal{G}_{n,m}$. Inside it are two smaller, disjoint regions labeled $CM(n, \mathbf{k}^1)$ and $CM(n, \mathbf{k}^2)$. At the bottom of the diagram is the equation $\sum k_1 = \sum k^1 = 2m$.]}
\end{figure}

\item ER is not a ``bad model'' of the degree distribution; it simply has a specific ``maximally random'' value (binomial).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Theorem 10.1.} \textit{The binomial distribution} $\text{Bin}[n-1, p](k)$ \textit{is the maximum-entropy distribution across all the distributions that are sums of $n-1$ independent Bernoullis (of different success rates, in general) under the constrain $\bar{k} = (n-1)p$. (P. Harremos, 2001)}

\textbf{Remember:} Any network property has some specific value or distribution in any network model, including ER and CM.

